eanings":[{"name":"Sutton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of numerous places called Sutton, named with Old English <i>sūth</i> ‘south, southern’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. The English surname is also common in Ireland (Wexford, Kildare), where it has been established since the 13th century and Gaelicized as <b>de Sutún</b>.","Jewish (from the former Ottoman Empire, including Syria): unexplained.","English: topographic name from Middle English <i>(bi) suthentune</i> ‘(at the place to the) south of the village’."],"variants":[{"name":"Setton","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Avi, Ronit, Yossef.  French Andree, Henri, Jacques, Maryse.","Jewish (from the Ottoman Empire): altered form of   Sutton  .","English (Middlesex): variant of   Seaton  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":27,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert Sutton was born about 1355, in Lincoln, Lincolnshire, England, his father, John Sutton of Lincoln, was 37 and his mother, Sutton, was 36. He had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Agnes. In 1381, his occupation is listed as member of parliament for lincoln. He died on 15 April 1414, in his hometown, at the age of 60, and was buried in Lincolnshire, England."},"et":{"about 1355–15 April 1414":"umbes 1355–15. aprill 1414","1345–1391":"1345–1391","1350–Female":"1350–Surnud","1355–1414":"1355–1414","1360–Male":"1360–Surnud","1370–1427":"1370–1427","1392–1461":"1392–1461","–Female":"Surnud","1320–1378":"1320–1378","1320–Female":"1320–Surnud","about 1392":"umbes 1392","1461":"1461","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","1392":"1392","1370":"1370","1391":"1391","between 1381 and 1399":"1381 kuni 1399","1414":"1414","1378":"1378","1345":"1345","1355":"1355","1320":"1320","about 1355":"umbes 1355","15 April 1414":"15. aprill 1414","circa 1378":"umbes 1378","from 1379 to 1380":"1379 kuni 1380","1427":"1427","Lincoln, Lincolnshire, England":"Lincoln, Lincolnshire, England","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England"},"fi":{"about 1355–15 April 1414":"noin 1355–15. huhtikuuta 1414","1345–1391":"1345–1391","1350–Female":"1350–Kuollut","1355–1414":"1355–1414","1360–Male":"1360–Kuollut","1370–1427":"1370–1427","1392–1461":"1392–1461","–Female":"Kuollut","1320–1378":"1320–1378","1320–Female":"1320–Kuollut","about 1392":"noin 1392","1461":"1461","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","1392":"1392","1370":"1370","1391":"1391","between 1381 and 1399":"vuodesta 1381 vuoteen 1399","1